---
import ReportLayout from '@/components/ReportLayout.astro';
---

<ReportLayout title="Figma Engineering Handover Agent">

  <section class="agent-intro">
    <p class="agent-eyebrow">Agent Guide</p>
    <h1 class="agent-h1">Figma Engineering Handover</h1>
    <p class="agent-summary">
      The Engineering Handover agent reads a Figma frame and produces a structured spec for the
      engineering team — covering every element in the component tree with its Tailwind classes,
      spacing, typography, colours, and assets to export. Because engineers have view-only Figma
      access (no Dev Mode), all values are explicitly documented so nothing needs to be looked up.
      The agent maps values directly to classes from the project's Tailwind config, and flags
      anything that has no token or needs a design decision before build.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Output mode callout ────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="output-modes">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Two output modes</h2>
    <div class="mode-cards">

      <div class="mode-card">
        <div class="mode-icon">✦</div>
        <div class="mode-body">
          <h3 class="mode-title">Text report</h3>
          <p class="mode-desc">
            A structured markdown document you can copy and paste into Slack, Notion, Linear, or
            wherever your team manages handovers. Organised element-by-element — each section of the
            component lists all its Tailwind classes together, so the engineer can build top-down
            without cross-referencing multiple tables.
          </p>
          <p class="mode-trigger">Say: <em>"give me a handover for this Figma frame"</em></p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="mode-card">
        <div class="mode-icon">◈</div>
        <div class="mode-body">
          <h3 class="mode-title">Figma annotations</h3>
          <p class="mode-desc">
            The agent writes the spec directly into your Figma file as an annotation panel next to
            the component. Each element has its own card showing the property label and its Tailwind
            class — warnings in orange for anything untokenised or needing clarification. The design
            stays untouched; the annotations live alongside it on the same page.
          </p>
          <p class="mode-trigger">Say: <em>"add the handover annotations to the Figma file"</em></p>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Before you start ────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="guide-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Before you start</h2>
    <ul class="checklist">
      <li>
        The Figma URL of the specific frame you want documented — make sure it includes a
        <code>node-id</code> parameter (right-click a frame in Figma → Copy link to selection)
      </li>
      <li>
        The Figma MCP must be connected — check that the Figma plugin is running in Claude Code
        before triggering the agent
      </li>
      <li>
        For the most accurate class name mapping, the Tailwind config reference should be up to date
        at <code>skills/figma-engineering-handover/references/tailwind.config.md</code>. Without it,
        the agent falls back to Tailwind defaults and flags the caveat at the top of the output
      </li>
      <li>
        If you want Figma annotations, make sure you have edit access to the file — the agent
        needs to write to it
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <!-- ── How to trigger ──────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="guide-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">How to trigger it</h2>
    <p class="guide-body">Paste the Figma URL and describe what you want:</p>
    <div class="trigger-examples">
      <span class="trigger-chip">"give me a handover for this frame [URL]"</span>
      <span class="trigger-chip">"write this up for the engineers [URL]"</span>
      <span class="trigger-chip">"prep the handover for this component [URL]"</span>
      <span class="trigger-chip">"add the handover annotations to the Figma file [URL]"</span>
      <span class="trigger-chip">"what do the engineers need to build this? [URL]"</span>
    </div>
    <p class="guide-body guide-body--tip">
      The agent will produce a text report by default. If you want Figma annotations instead —
      or as well — say so explicitly in your message.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Step-by-step walkthrough ───────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="guide-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Step-by-step walkthrough</h2>
    <ol class="steps">
      <li class="step">
        <span class="step-number">1</span>
        <div class="step-body">
          <h3 class="step-title">Load the Tailwind config reference</h3>
          <p class="step-desc">
            The agent reads the stored Tailwind config reference to understand what classes exist
            in the project. This is what lets it output <code>bg-surface</code> rather than
            <code>#f2f2f2</code>, and <code>text-primary-500</code> rather than
            <code>#003942</code>. If the reference file is missing, it continues with Tailwind
            defaults and notes the caveat at the top of the output.
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li class="step">
        <span class="step-number">2</span>
        <div class="step-body">
          <h3 class="step-title">Read the Figma frame</h3>
          <p class="step-desc">
            The agent pulls three things from Figma in parallel: a screenshot of the frame for
            visual reference, the design context (layout, spacing, typography, colour values), and
            the variable definitions — the token names actually applied to elements in the file.
            This is how it knows which Figma token corresponds to which resolved hex value.
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li class="step">
        <span class="step-number">3</span>
        <div class="step-body">
          <h3 class="step-title">Map tokens to classes</h3>
          <p class="step-desc">
            Every Figma token is matched against the Tailwind config. Colours, spacing, border
            radius, and typography are all mapped to their real class names. Anything without a
            match — colours applied as raw hex, values that fall between Tailwind scale steps,
            untokenised backgrounds — is flagged with a ⚠️ and a note explaining what needs
            resolving before build.
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li class="step">
        <span class="step-number">4</span>
        <div class="step-body">
          <h3 class="step-title">Write the handover</h3>
          <p class="step-desc">
            The output is organised element-by-element, walking the component tree top-down. Each
            element — container, sub-container, text node, badge, button — gets its own section
            listing all its properties together: display, gap, padding, background, border radius,
            overflow, font size, weight, colour, and line height. No cross-referencing separate
            tables. The assets section lists every SVG and image that needs exporting from Figma,
            with format and size. Open questions are collected at the bottom for the designer or
            engineer to resolve.
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li class="step">
        <span class="step-number">5</span>
        <div class="step-body">
          <h3 class="step-title">Optionally write Figma annotations</h3>
          <p class="step-desc">
            If you asked for Figma annotations, the agent creates an annotation panel to the right
            of your component on the same page. It builds one card per major section —
            Product Card, Top Container, Image Container, Product Container, Price &amp; CTA — each
            showing the property label in grey and the Tailwind class in teal. Warnings appear in
            orange. The design frame itself is not touched.
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </section>

  <!-- ── What the output looks like ────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="guide-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">What the output looks like</h2>

    <h3 class="sub-heading">Text report structure</h3>
    <p class="guide-body">Every report follows this structure:</p>
    <ul class="file-list">
      <li><strong>Token → class reference</strong> — a lookup table of every Figma variable token and its Tailwind class, for the engineer to verify against their config</li>
      <li><strong>Component structure</strong> — a plain-text tree showing how the component divides into sections</li>
      <li><strong>Component breakdown</strong> — one section per element, each listing all its Tailwind classes together in a property/class table</li>
      <li><strong>Assets to export</strong> — every SVG, icon, and image with format and intrinsic size</li>
      <li><strong>Open questions</strong> — specific items that need a designer or engineering decision before build can start</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="sub-heading">How values are expressed</h3>
    <p class="guide-body">
      All values use Tailwind class names from the project config — never raw pixel values.
      Font sizes use the named scale (<code>text-xs</code>, <code>text-sm</code>,
      <code>text-base</code>). Spacing uses the numeric scale (<code>gap-2</code>,
      <code>px-4</code>). Colours use the project's semantic classes (<code>bg-surface</code>,
      <code>text-primary-500</code>, <code>bg-accent-100/40</code>). Where a value has no token,
      it's written as an arbitrary value (<code>rounded-[32px]</code>) and flagged for review.
    </p>

    <h3 class="sub-heading">Figma annotation panel</h3>
    <p class="guide-body">
      The Figma annotation panel sits to the right of the component on the same page. It uses the
      same element-by-element structure as the text report — one card per major section, each with
      a bold teal header and a two-column layout of property labels and class values. Warnings
      appear in orange so they're immediately visible. The panel is a grouped Figma frame — it can
      be moved, hidden, or deleted without affecting the design.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Keeping the config up to date ─────────────────────── -->
  <section class="guide-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Keeping the Tailwind config up to date</h2>
    <p class="guide-body">
      The agent's accuracy depends on the stored Tailwind config reference. When the engineering
      team updates their config — adding new tokens, changing colour values, extending the spacing
      scale — the reference file should be updated to match.
    </p>
    <h3 class="sub-heading">Where the reference lives</h3>
    <p class="guide-body">
      <code>skills/figma-engineering-handover/references/tailwind.config.md</code>
    </p>
    <p class="guide-body">
      The file contains the colour token map (Figma token → hex → Tailwind class), font size
      scale, spacing scale, border radius scale, and breakpoints. Ask the engineering team for
      their latest <code>tailwind.config.js</code> and <code>themes/index.js</code> whenever
      the config changes, then paste the updated values into this file.
    </p>
    <p class="guide-body guide-body--tip">
      The themes file matters as much as the config — colours are defined as oklch CSS variables
      in the theme, not as hex values in the config. Without the theme file, colour class names
      can't be verified against their resolved hex values.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Tips and common issues ────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="guide-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Tips and common issues</h2>
    <ul class="tips-list">
      <li>
        <strong>Use a node-specific Figma URL.</strong>
        The URL must include a <code>node-id</code> parameter pointing to the specific frame.
        A file-level URL (no node-id) will return the whole file, not the component you want.
        Right-click the frame in Figma → Copy link to selection to get the right URL.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Warnings are expected — they're part of the output.</strong>
        ⚠️ flags in the report don't mean the agent has failed. They mean something needs a
        decision before build: a missing token, an untokenised colour, a non-standard line height.
        Treat the open questions section as a checklist to work through with the designer before
        handing off to engineering.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Line heights often need an arbitrary value.</strong>
        Tailwind's font size scale pairs each size with a default line height, but designs
        frequently use a different line height than the pair (e.g. 14px text with 18px line
        height). The agent flags these and uses <code>leading-[18px]</code>. Ask the engineering
        team whether to add a named token to the config or use the arbitrary value throughout.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Figma annotations don't update automatically.</strong>
        If the design changes after annotations have been added, the annotation panel won't update
        on its own. Delete the old panel and ask the agent to re-run the annotation step with the
        updated frame URL.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>The Figma plugin must be running for annotations.</strong>
        Figma write operations require the Figma MCP plugin to be active. If the agent says it
        can't write to Figma, check that the plugin is running in the Figma desktop app and that
        you have edit access to the file.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

</ReportLayout>

<style>
  .agent-intro { margin-bottom: 48px; }
  .agent-eyebrow {
    font-size: 12px;
    font-weight: 700;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.1em;
    color: var(--color-primary);
    opacity: 0.5;
    margin-bottom: 10px;
  }
  .agent-h1 {
    font-size: clamp(26px, 4vw, 38px);
    font-weight: 800;
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
    margin-bottom: 16px;
    line-height: 1.15;
  }
  .agent-summary {
    font-size: 15px;
    line-height: 1.7;
    color: var(--color-text-body);
    max-width: 680px;
  }

  .output-modes { margin-bottom: 52px; }
  .mode-cards {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    gap: 16px;
    margin-top: 20px;
  }
  @media (max-width: 640px) { .mode-cards { grid-template-columns: 1fr; } }
  .mode-card {
    display: flex;
    gap: 16px;
    background: var(--color-bg-card);
    border: var(--card-border);
    border-radius: var(--radius-card);
    padding: 20px;
  }
  .mode-icon {
    font-size: 20px;
    color: var(--color-primary);
    opacity: 0.4;
    flex-shrink: 0;
    margin-top: 2px;
  }
  .mode-title {
    font-size: 15px;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
    margin-bottom: 8px;
  }
  .mode-desc {
    font-size: 13px;
    line-height: 1.65;
    color: var(--color-text-body);
    margin-bottom: 10px;
  }
  .mode-trigger {
    font-size: 12px;
    color: var(--color-text-body);
    background: var(--color-bg-muted);
    border-radius: 6px;
    padding: 6px 10px;
  }
  .mode-trigger em { color: var(--color-primary); font-style: normal; font-weight: 500; }

  .guide-section { margin-bottom: 52px; }
  .section-heading {
    font-size: 20px;
    font-weight: 800;
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
    margin-bottom: 16px;
    padding-bottom: 10px;
    border-bottom: 2px solid rgba(0,57,66,0.08);
  }
  .sub-heading {
    font-size: 14px;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
    margin: 20px 0 8px;
  }

  .guide-body {
    font-size: 14px;
    line-height: 1.65;
    color: var(--color-text-body);
    margin-bottom: 16px;
  }
  .guide-body--tip {
    background: var(--color-bg-muted);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--color-mint);
    padding: 10px 14px;
    border-radius: 0 6px 6px 0;
    margin-top: 12px;
  }

  .checklist {
    list-style: none;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 10px;
  }
  .checklist li {
    font-size: 14px;
    line-height: 1.6;
    color: var(--color-text-body);
    padding-left: 22px;
    position: relative;
  }
  .checklist li::before {
    content: '→';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    color: var(--color-primary);
    opacity: 0.4;
    font-size: 13px;
  }

  .trigger-examples {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 8px;
    margin-bottom: 14px;
  }
  .trigger-chip {
    font-size: 13px;
    background: var(--color-bg-muted);
    border: var(--card-border);
    border-radius: var(--radius-chip);
    padding: 5px 12px;
    color: var(--color-text-body);
    font-style: italic;
  }

  code {
    font-family: 'SF Mono', 'Fira Code', monospace;
    font-size: 12.5px;
    background: var(--color-bg-muted);
    color: var(--color-primary);
    padding: 2px 6px;
    border-radius: 4px;
  }

  .file-list {
    list-style: none;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 8px;
    margin-bottom: 4px;
  }
  .file-list li {
    font-size: 14px;
    color: var(--color-text-body);
    line-height: 1.6;
    padding-left: 16px;
    position: relative;
  }
  .file-list li::before {
    content: '·';
    position: absolute;
    left: 4px;
    color: var(--color-primary);
    opacity: 0.4;
  }

  .steps { list-style: none; display: flex; flex-direction: column; }
  .step {
    display: flex;
    gap: 20px;
    align-items: flex-start;
    padding: 24px 0;
    border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(0,57,66,0.08);
  }
  .step:last-child { border-bottom: none; }
  .step-number {
    flex-shrink: 0;
    width: 34px;
    height: 34px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    background: var(--color-primary);
    color: var(--color-mint);
    font-size: 13px;
    font-weight: 800;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    margin-top: 2px;
  }
  .step-title {
    font-size: 15px;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
    margin-bottom: 6px;
  }
  .step-desc {
    font-size: 14px;
    line-height: 1.65;
    color: var(--color-text-body);
  }

  .tips-list {
    list-style: none;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 16px;
  }
  .tips-list li {
    font-size: 14px;
    line-height: 1.65;
    color: var(--color-text-body);
    background: var(--color-bg-card);
    border: var(--card-border);
    border-radius: var(--radius-card);
    padding: 16px 18px;
  }
  .tips-list strong {
    display: block;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
    margin-bottom: 4px;
  }
</style>
